<h2>U.S. Government Course Overview</h2>

<p>
Welcome to U.S. Government. This course is designed to help students understand the principles, structures, and functions of the American political system. Students will study the Constitution, federalism, the branches of government, civil liberties and rights, political participation, public policy, and civic responsibility.
</p>

<p>
This course follows a competency-based model. Students progress by demonstrating mastery of course expectations rather than by seat time. Each unit and lesson must be completed in sequence.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Course Information</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Grade Level: 11</li>
  <li>Credit Value: 0.5</li>
  <li>Subject Area: Social Studies</li>
  <li>Course Type: Core Requirement</li>
  <li>Prerequisite: U.S. History</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h3>Course Structure</h3>

<p>
The course is organized into six sequential, mastery-based units:
</p>

<ol>
  <li>Foundations of Government and Civic Thinking</li>
  <li>Constitutional Principles and Federalism</li>
  <li>Branches of Government and Checks and Balances</li>
  <li>Civil Liberties, Civil Rights, and Law</li>
  <li>Political Participation, Elections, and Media</li>
  <li>Public Policy, Citizenship, and Modern Governance</li>
</ol>

<p>
Each unit includes a pretest, lesson instruction, Notebook Evidence, Checkpoint submissions, lesson quizzes, and a Unit Final Assessment.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Required Learning Sequence</h3>

<p>
Students must complete course activities in the order presented. Each activity unlocks only after required completion of the previous activity.
</p>

<ol>
  <li>Complete the Course Orientation and Expectations section</li>
  <li>Complete the Course Acknowledgment</li>
  <li>Complete the Unit Pretest</li>
  <li>Complete each lesson in sequence</li>
  <li>Submit Notebook Evidence for each lesson</li>
  <li>Submit the Checkpoint for each lesson</li>
  <li>Earn 80% or higher on each lesson quiz</li>
  <li>Complete the Unit Final Assessment</li>
  <li>Maintain an overall course average of 80% or higher to continue progressing</li>
</ol>

<hr>

<h3>Pretest Policy</h3>

<p>
Each unit begins with a pretest. The pretest is diagnostic only and does not count toward the course grade. It is used to assess current understanding and determine the most appropriate learning path.
</p>

<p>
Students who score 90% or higher may be eligible for an accelerated path for that unit. Acceleration is not automatic. A parent/guardian request and administrative approval are required.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Notebook Evidence</h3>

<p>
Notebook Evidence allows students to record thinking, organize learning, and demonstrate understanding of lesson content. Submissions are reviewed and graded by the Teacher of Record using a mastery-based rubric.
</p>

<p>
Notebook Evidence must meet mastery expectations before progression.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Checkpoint Submissions</h3>

<p>
Checkpoints are lesson-based mastery tasks used to demonstrate readiness for the lesson quiz. These are reviewed and graded by the Teacher of Record.
</p>

<p>
Students must meet mastery expectations before progressing.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Lesson Quiz Policy</h3>

<p>
Each lesson quiz allows two attempts. Students must earn a score of 80% or higher to move to the next lesson.
</p>

<p>
If a student does not earn 80% or higher on the first attempt, the student is expected to review lesson content and seek support before the second attempt.
</p>

<p>
Failure to earn 80% or higher after two attempts may require additional review before progression is allowed.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Unit Final Assessment</h3>

<p>
Each unit concludes with a cumulative Unit Final Assessment. This assessment must be completed.
</p>

<p>
Progression is based on the overall course average, not the Unit Final Assessment score alone. Students must maintain an overall course average of 80% or higher to continue progressing.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Credit and Mastery Requirements</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Complete all six units</li>
  <li>Complete all Notebook Evidence submissions</li>
  <li>Complete all Checkpoint submissions</li>
  <li>Earn 80% or higher on lesson quizzes</li>
  <li>Complete all Unit Final Assessments</li>
  <li>Maintain an overall course average of 80% or higher</li>
</ul>

<p>
There is no seat-time requirement. Credit is awarded upon demonstrated mastery.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Feedback and Revision</h3>

<p>
Students receive feedback from the Teacher of Record. Revision may be required when mastery has not yet been demonstrated.
</p>

<p>
Revision is expected and is part of the learning process.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Academic Integrity and Use of AI</h3>

<p>
Students must submit original work. AI tools may be used only within course guidelines and may not replace the student’s own thinking.
</p>

<p>
Misuse of AI or academic dishonesty may result in required resubmission or additional academic review.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Accessibility and Support</h3>

<p>
This course supports diverse learners through structured pacing, mastery-based grading, revision opportunities, and guidance from the Teacher of Record.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Course Alignment</h3>

<p>
This course aligns with Florida U.S. Government standards, college and career readiness expectations, and Mindful Learning Academy’s competency-based instructional model.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Course Completion</h3>

<p>
Credit is awarded after successful completion of all required course components and mastery requirements.
</p>

<p>
Students are expected to progress carefully, complete all work in sequence, and use feedback to strengthen understanding.
</p>